 of Indigenous narrative and representation in contemporary Indigenous media. Focussing primarily on the Aboriginal Peoples Television Network, the authors also examine Indigenous language broadcasting in radio, television, and film; Aboriginal journalism practices; audience creation within and beyond Indigenous communities; the roles of program scheduling and content acquisition policies in the decolonization process; the roles of digital video technologies and co-production agreements in Indigenous filmmaking; and the emergence of Aboriginal cyber-communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian motion pictureszCanada. 0aMass mediazCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBaltruschat, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBredin, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBredin, Marian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavid, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHafsteinsson, SIGURJóN BALDUR, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHafsteinsson, Sigurjon Baldur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnopf, Kerstin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatterson, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, Yvonne poitras, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamsay, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Lorna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978